'''Francesc "Cesc" Fàbregas Soler''' ({{IPA-ca|ˈsɛsk ˈfaβɾəɣəs|lang}}; born 4 May 1987) is a Spanish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] for English club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]]. 

Fàbregas came through ''[[La Masia]]'', [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]'s youth academy, leaving at 16 when he was signed by English Premier League side [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in September 2003. Following injuries to key midfielders in the early part of the [[2004–05 in English football|2004–05 season]], he went on establish himself  in the team. He broke several of the club's records in the process, earning a reputation as one of the best players in his position, and won the [[FA Cup]] in 2005. After a protracted transfer saga Fàbregas left London on 15 August 2011 to return to Barcelona in a deal worth up to £35 million. During his three-year spell at the [[Camp Nou]], Fàbregas played in alongside [[Xavi]] and [[Andrés Iniesta]] and won a [[2012–13 La Liga|La Liga]] title, the [[2011–12 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]], the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]], the [[2011 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] and two [[Supercopa de España|Spanish Super Cups]]. He returned to London in June 2014 to Arsenal's cross-town rivals Chelsea for a fee of £30 million, and in his first year there he helped to secure [[League Cup]] and Premier League triumphs.

Internationally, Fàbregas made his debut for the Spanish national team in March 2006. He represented his country in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2008]], [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]], [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2012]], [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup]] and the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. He was a key figure in Spain's European Championship victories in 2008 and 2012 and their 2010 World Cup triumph in which he supplied the pass for Andrés Iniesta's winning goal in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|final]]. On 12 October 2015, Fàbregas  earned his [[FIFA Century Club|100th cap]] for Spain.

== Early years ==
Born in [[Arenys de Mar]], [[Province of Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]],<ref name=espn>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=38886&cc=4716 Francesc Fabregas profile], ESPNsoccernet, accessed 27 June 2009.</ref><ref name=ars>[http://www.arsenal.com/first-team/players/cesc-fabregas Cesc Fàbregas profile], Arsenal F.C., accessed 27 June 2009.</ref> to Francesc Fàbregas Sr., who runs a property company, and Núria Soler, the owner of a pastry company, Fàbregas has supported [[FC Barcelona]] since childhood and went to his first match when he was nine months old with his grandfather.<ref>[http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/francesc-fabregas-spanish-marvel-blossoms-out-of-the-world-of-his-mentors-509243.html Francesc Fabregas: Spanish marvel blossoms out of the world of his mentors], ''[[The Independent]]'', accessed 31 August 2010.</ref> He began his club football career with [[CE Mataró]] before being signed for Barcelona's ''[[La Masia]]'' youth academy aged ten in 1997.<ref>[http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/todo/era/sueno/elppordep/20060516elpepidep_6/Tes Cuando todo era un sueño], ELPAÍS.com, accessed 16 May 2006</ref> His first coach, Señor Blai, reportedly did not select Fàbregas for matches against Barcelona in an attempt to hide him from their scouts.<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/blog/2010/mar/31/cesc-fabregas-barcelona-arsenal Cesc Fàbregas faces the Barcelona Dream Team he left behind], ''The Guardian'', 31 March 2010, accessed 18 September 2010.</ref> This tactic, however, was unable to withstand Barcelona for long, and Mataró gave in and allowed Fàbregas to train with Barcelona one day per week. Eventually Fàbregas joined Barcelona's academy full-time. His initial training was as a [[defensive midfielder]] playing alongside notable names such as [[Gerard Piqué]] and [[Lionel Messi]]. Although he was a prolific scorer, sometimes scoring even more than 30 goals in a season for the club's youth teams, he did not manage to play a first team game at the [[Camp Nou]].<ref name=uefap>[http://www.uefa.com/competitions/UCL/players/player=70072/index.html Cesc Fabregas], UEFA, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> During his time at Barcelona's youth academy, Fàbregas idolised Barcelona's then-captain and number four [[Pep Guardiola]], who would later give Fàbregas his shirt as consolation when Fàbregas' parents divorced.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/8718064.stm The one that got away], BBC Sport, accessed 1 June 2010.</ref>

== Club career ==

=== Arsenal ===

==== Adapting to England ====

[[File:Fabregas shooting.jpg|thumb|Fàbregas (left) in a game against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 2006]]
Sensing that he would have limited opportunities at Barcelona,<ref name=fa>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080820045904/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/04/FACF_CescFabregasPreview.htm The Young Gunner], The Football Association, 19 May 2005, accessed 27 August 2011.</ref> Fàbregas joined [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in their [[Arsenal F.C. Academy|Academy]],<ref name="PFA 200">{{Cite book| last = Hugman| first = Barry J.| title = The PFA Premier & Football League Players' Records 1946–2005| publisher = Queen Anne Press| year = 2005| page = 200| isbn = 1-85291-665-6 }}</ref> signing for the London club on 11 September 2003.<ref name=ars/> Initially, he found life difficult in England's capital but soon struck a friendship with Spanish-speaking teammate [[Philippe Senderos]], who helped him settle down.<ref name=times>Marcotti, Gabriele and Balague, Guillem, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premiership/arsenal/article1449871.ece "From Barcelona to Barnet: how a rising star learnt his trade"], ''The Times'', 28 February 2007, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> As a 16-year-old, Fàbregas did not contemplate breaking into the first team immediately but looked up to senior players like [[Patrick Vieira]] and [[Gilberto Silva]], while concentrating on training and learning the English language.<ref name=times/> He nevertheless made his debut for Arsenal not long after, on 28 October 2003, in a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] tie at home to [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]]. In doing so, he became Arsenal's youngest-ever first team player, aged 16 years and 177 days.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-becomes-youngest-gunner Cesc Fabregas becomes Arsenal's youngest ever player], Arsenal F.C., 27 January 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He then became the youngest goalscorer in Arsenal's history in a later round of the League Cup, scoring in a 5–1 victory against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3246940.stm Arsenal youngsters thump Wolves], BBC Sport, 2 December 2003, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> Although Arsenal went on to [[The Invincibles (football)|win the league unbeaten]] in the [[2003–04 in English football|2003–04 season]],<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/history/club-records/record-scorelines Record Scorelines], Arsenal F.C., accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> Fàbregas was not awarded a winner's medal because he did not play a single league game.<ref name=stats>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/stats?id=38886&cc=4716 Francesc Fabregas history], ESPNsoccernet, accessed 18 December 2007.</ref>

It was not until the start of the [[2004–05 in English football|2004–05 season]] that the Spaniard started making first team appearances in matches outside the League Cup. His first match of the season was against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the [[FA Community Shield]]. Following an injury to Vieira, Fàbregas stepped in and made four consecutive Premier League starts. He was praised for his performances in those games, even claiming a goal against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in a 3–0 victory, and becoming Arsenal's youngest-ever goalscorer in a league game.<ref>Hughes, Ian, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/3600372.stm "Fabregas the fabulous"], BBC Sport, 27 August 2004, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref><ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=152167&cc=4716 Arsenal 3–0 Blackburn], ESPNsoccernet, 25 August 2004, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> With further injuries to [[Eduardo César Gaspar|Edu]] and Gilberto Silva, he received more playing time in all competitions.<ref name=espn/><ref name=fa/> He signed his first [[professional]] contract with Arsenal in September 2004,<ref name="PFA 200"/> which committed his long-term future to the club.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/3664918.stm Fabregas commits to Arsenal], BBC Sport, 17 September 2004, accessed 3 June 2010.</ref> In October 2004, Arsenal lost 2–0 to Manchester United, ending their 49-match unbeaten run in the Premier League. The match was dubbed the "[[Battle of the Buffet]]" after pizza was thrown at Manchester United manager [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] at the end of the match in the players' tunnel by a then-unknown Arsenal player. Speculation that the player was Fàbregas<ref name="whohitsiralex">{{cite news |title=Who hit Sir Alex with pizza?|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/sport/who-hit-sir-alex-with-pizza-6955390.html |publisher=standard.co.uk |date=27 October 2004 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref><ref name="Selfishlazy">{{cite news |title=Selfish, lazy youngsters cost Arsenal the season – Cole |url=http://www.standard.co.uk/sport/selfish-lazy-youngsters-cost-arsenal-the-season--cole-7201142.html |publisher=standard.co.uk |date=13 September 2006 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref><ref name="Toughtackling">{{cite news |title=Tough tackling Fabregas proves Arsenal are gunning for bullies, says Clichy|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-475725/Tough-tackling-Fabregas-proves-Arsenal-gunning-bullies-says-Clichy.html |publisher=Daily Mail |date=16 August 2007 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref> was confirmed in November 2011 by former Arsenal player [[Martin Keown]] on a phone-in show on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]].<ref name="Fabregasrevealed">{{cite news |title=Fabregas revealed as Gunner who fired pizza at Fergie|url=http://www.people.co.uk/sport/football/news/2011/11/13/fabregas-revealed-as-gunner-who-fired-pizza-at-fergie-102039-23557693/ |publisher=The People |date=13 November 2011 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref><ref name="Culprit">{{cite news |title=Fabregas confirmed as 'Battle of the Buffet' culprit who threw pizza at Sir Alex Ferguson|url=http://mancunianmatters.co.uk/content/15111678-fabregas-confirmed-battle-buffet-culprit-who-threw-pizza-sir-alex-ferguson |publisher=Mancunian Matters |date=15 November 2011 |accessdate=11 August 2012 }}</ref> In the [[2004–05 UEFA Champions League]], he became the second-youngest goalscorer in the competition's history after scoring the third goal against [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] in a 5–1 win.<ref>Haylett, Trevor, [http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2004/round=1968/match=1077234/index.html "Awesome Arsenal progress in style], UEFA, 7 December 2004, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He concluded his season by winning his first honours with Arsenal when he was in the starting eleven that defeated Manchester United on [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]] in the [[2005 FA Cup Final]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/4558271.stm Arsenal 0–0 Man Utd (aet)], BBC Sport, 21 May 2005, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref>

==== Making the starting eleven ====
After the departure of Patrick Vieira to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], Fàbregas was given the Frenchman's number 4 shirt and featured regularly in the Arsenal central midfield alongside Gilberto Silva. He made 49 appearances in all competitions during the [[2005–06 in English football|2005–06 season]].<ref name=stats/> Despite his young age, his performances came under greater scrutiny due to his increased involvement in the first team. Further, as Fàbregas possessed a smaller frame and played with less aggression than Vieira, there were initially doubts over his ability to fill in the void left by the Frenchman.<ref name=hubb>Hubbard, Norman, [http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=340141&root=england&cc=4716 "Arsenal's midfield muddle"], ESPNsoccernet, 22 August 2005, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> Nevertheless, Fàbregas asserted his own style of play and impressed pundits in the Champions League against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and Juventus.<ref name=bbc>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4841992.stm Arsenal 2–0 Juventus], BBC Sport, 28 March 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref>Sheringham, Sam, [http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=10000086&sid=aIRzsd9XXEPY&refer=latin_america "Spain Teenager Fabregas Sparks World Cup Rally, Wows Maradona"], Bloomberg, 20 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref name=harr>Harrold, Michael, [http://www.uefa.com/magazine/news/kind=512/newsid=527164.html "Fabregas plots Arsenal revival"], UEFA, 13 April 2007, accessed 23 May 2007. {{Wayback|df=yes|url=http://www.uefa.com/magazine/news/kind=512/newsid=527164.html|date =20070518174227|bot=DASHBot}}</ref> In the latter, he scored Arsenal's first goal and set up [[Thierry Henry]] for the second,<ref name=bbc/> at the same time proving that he could compete against tough, hard-tackling midfielders like Vieira.<ref name=harr/> He then played in the [[2006 UEFA Champions League Final|Final]] against his former club Barcelona, but Arsenal were defeated 2–1,<ref>Haslam, Andrew, [http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2005/round=2205/match=1108503/index.html "Barca comeback denies Arsenal"], UEFA, 17 May 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> completing a trophyless 2005–06 campaign for Arsenal.

[[File:Fabregas celebration.jpg|thumb|upright|Fàbregas celebrates a goal with his Arsenal teammates]]
Fàbregas' increase in exposure drew transfer speculation during the summer; Real Madrid expressed a desire to sign the Spaniard despite his long-term contract with Arsenal,<ref>Kendall, Mark, [http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_2382489,00.html "Real confident of securing Cesc's signature"], Sky Sports, 4 July 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> but Arsenal manager [[Arsène Wenger]] stated that Arsenal would not listen to any offers.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/wenger-fabregas-is-not-for-sale-he-is-arsenal-rsquo-s-future Wenger: Fàbregas is not for sale, he is Arsenal's future], Arsenal F.C., 12 July 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> In September 2006, with six years left on his deal, Arsenal offered a new five-year deal (with an option to extend by a further three years) to the midfielder, which he signed on 19 October 2006.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/5340362.stm Fàbregas signs new Arsenal deal], BBC Sport, 19 October 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> While the contract was unusually long, Fàbregas cited Arsenal's playing style and Wenger as reasons for his long-term commitment to the club.<ref>Harris, Chris, [http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-our-style-of-play-makes-me-so-happy "Fabregas – Our style of play makes me so happy"], Arsenal F.C., 22 October 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref>Adams, Tom, [http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_2393205,00.html "Cesc staying grounded"], Sky Sports, 27 October 2006, accessed 24 May 2007.</ref>

[[File:Cesc Fàbregas captain.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Fàbregas was appointed captain of the team during the 2008–09 season]]
The [[2006–07 in English football|2006–07 season]] was a learning experience for the young Arsenal squad and Fàbregas. The club again failed to secure any major honours and were defeated by city rivals [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[Football League Cup Final 2007|League Cup Final]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/6371613.stm Chelsea 2–1 Arsenal], BBC Sport, 21 February 2007, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> However, Fàbregas emerged as one of the key creative players for the team, playing in every single league game.<ref name=stats/><ref name=actim>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/arsenal-are-the-ultimate-second-half-team Arsenal are the ultimate 'second half' team], Arsenal F.C., accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> He kick-started Arsenal's [[UEFA Champions League 2006-07|2006–07 UEFA Champions League]] campaign when he scored a brace in a 3–0 win over [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] in a qualifier match.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5251984.stm Dinamo Zagreb 0–3 Arsenal], BBC Sport, 8 June 2006, accessed 7 September 2008.</ref> In the Premier League, he notched up 13 [[assist (soccer)|assists]], which was the second-highest total in the league.<ref name=stats/><ref name=actim/> He ended the season with several individual honours, including the Golden Boy award, presented by the Italian paper ''TuttoSport'', based on a poll of leading writers across Europe.<ref>Lipton, Martin, [http://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/tm_headline=he-s-fab-in-poll%26method=full%26objectid=18196769%26siteid=94762-name_page.html "HE'S FAB IN POLL"], ''Daily Mirror'', 2 December 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He was also named in the 2006 [[UEFA Team of the Year]],<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/fanzone/teamoftheyear/news/newsid=497866.html Your Team of 2006 revealed], UEFA, 19 January 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> and named [[FA Premier League Player of the Month]] for January 2007.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6348331.stm Benitez and Fabregas scoop awards], BBC Sport, 9 February 2007, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> Additionally, he was nominated for both [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] and [[PFA Young Player of the Year]], although both awards went to Manchester United's [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=215178&cc=4716 Arsenal 3–1 Man City: Fabregas inspires revival], ESPNsoccernet, 17 April 2007, accessed 18 April 2007.</ref> In June 2007, he was named Arsenal's Player of the Season, taking in 60% of the votes.<ref name=pots>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/-he-showed-he-is-the-ultimate-midfield-player- 'He showed he is the ultimate midfield player'], Arsenal F.C., accessed 28 June 2007.</ref>

The [[2007–08 in English football|2007–08 season]] began with much uncertainty for Arsenal. First, [[David Dein]], the club's vice-chairman, left amidst allegations of internal strife, followed by the departure of the club's all-time top goalscorer and captain, Thierry Henry, who signed for Barcelona. There was also speculation over Wenger's future with the club.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=460716&cc=4716 Wenger signs new three-year Gunners deal], ESPNsoccernet, 7 September 2007, accessed 16 September 2007.</ref> Fàbregas knew that he would become the most important player for Arsenal, but stated he was ready for the challenge.<ref name=chall>[http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,2156108,00.html How Fabregas plans to save Arsenal], ''The Guardian'', 25 August 2007, accessed 17 September 2007.</ref> He started the season well, chalking up goals and assists,<ref name=stats/> and website [[soccernet]] attributed the early success of Arsenal to the young Spaniard.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=463322&root=england&cc=4716&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab1pos3 Burying the ghost of Henry]. ESPNsoccernet, 15 September 2007, accessed 17 September 2007.</ref> His start to the season also earned him the [[O2 (UK)|O<sub>2</sub>]] Player of the Month award from Arsenal fans for August, September and October,<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-scoops-o2-player-of-the-month-award Fabregas scoops O2 Player of the Month award], Arsenal F.C., 5 October 2007, accessed 6 October 2007.</ref> as well as the Premier League Player of the Month for September.<ref>[http://www.premierleague.com/staticFiles/d1/a4/0,,12306~107729,00.pdf GUNNERS DUO CELEBRATE AWARDS DOUBLE], Premier League, 19 October 2007, accessed 5 March 2008.</ref> With Arsenal leading the league table until March, Fàbregas was equally instrumental in the club's [[UEFA Champions League 2007-08|2007–08 Champions League campaign]]; in the return leg against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], the midfielder scored late in the game to send Arsenal into the quarter-finals.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7272514.stm AC Milan 0 – Arsenal 2], BBC Sport, 5 March 2008, accessed 5 March 2008.</ref> Though Arsenal ended the season trophyless,<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/season-review-week-the-highlights-and-the-lowlights Season Review Week: The highlights and the lowlights], Arsenal F.C., accessed 24 May 2008.</ref> Fàbregas amassed several personal awards. On 11 April 2008, Fàbregas was nominated for the PFA Player of the Year and PFA Young Player of the Year awards for the second year running;<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=524778&cc=4716 Ronaldo heads shortlist for players' awards], ESPNsoccernet, 11 April 2008, accessed 12 April 2008.</ref> he was later crowned the winner of the latter, and named in the [[PFA Team of the Year#Premier League|PFA Team of the Year]]. He was also named the 2007–08 Arsenal.com Player of the Season.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-is-arsenal.com-player-of-the-season Fabregas is O2/Arsenal.com Player of the Season], Arsenal F.C., accessed 8 July 2008.</ref>

==== Captaincy ====

[[File:Ferdinand Fabregas.jpg|thumb|upright|Fàbregas as captain during the 2008–09 Champions League semi-final]]
On 24 November 2008, 14 league games into the [[2008–09 in English football|2008–09 season]], Fàbregas was named as the successor to [[William Gallas]] as club captain.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=595659&sec=uefachampionsleague&cc=4716 Fabregas replaces Gallas as Arsenal skipper], ESPNsoccernet, 24 November 2008, accessed 25 November 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.thesportreview.com/tsr/2008/11/captain-cescs-appointment-is-no-surpise/ Captain Cesc's appointment is no surprise], The Sport Review, 26 November 2008, accessed 22 May 2009.</ref> However, just as Arsenal were getting back into the title race after a poor start to the season, the Spaniard was ruled out for four months after sustaining a knee injury against Liverpool.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=604874&sec=england&cc=4716 Injured Fabregas ruled out for 3–4 months], ESPNsoccernet, 23 December 2008, accessed 24 December 2008.</ref> The Gunners eventually finished the season without any silverware, coming in fourth in the league and being knocked out at the semi-finals of the [[UEFA Champions League 2008–09|2008–09 Champions League campaign]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/team/stats?id=359&season=2008&league=eng.1&cc=4716 2008/2009 English Premier League: Statistics], ESPNsoccernet, accessed 1 July 2009.</ref><ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=266495&cc=4716&league=UEFA.CHAMPIONS Arsenal 1 – 3 Manchester United], ESPNsoccernet, 29 April 2009, accessed 1 July 2009.</ref> In tandem with Arsenal's policy to groom its young players, the team that Fàbregas led into the new season consisted mostly of the same young nucleus as before, with the likes of [[Nicklas Bendtner]], [[Gaël Clichy]], [[Abou Diaby]], [[Denílson Pereira Neves|Denílson]], [[Samir Nasri]], [[Alexandre Song]] and [[Theo Walcott]] in tow.

[[File:Jermaine Jenas, Cesc Fabregas & Younes Kaboul.jpg|thumb|left|Fàbregas in a game against rivals [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in November 2010]]
In the opening league game of [[2009–10 in English football|2009–10 season]], Fàbregas scored a brace and managed two assists in Arsenal's 6–1 away win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=269878&cc=5901&league=ENG.1 Gunners crush Toffees], ESPNsoccernet, 15 August 2009, accessed 18 August 2009.</ref> Arsenal went on to secure qualification for the [[UEFA Champions League 2009–10|2009–10 Champions League campaign]] by beating [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] over two legs, but their early momentum to the season was disrupted by consecutive league game losses to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. The team bounced back strongly after this setback, and with Fàbregas being prolific in scoring and setting up his teammates, it went unbeaten in the next 13 games. Despite suffering four league losses even before mid-season approached, Arsenal managed to lead the league standings after 22 games. On 31 March 2010, in the Champions League first leg of the quarter-final against Barcelona, Fàbregas suffered a leg fracture before scoring the equalising goal in the game which ended 2–2.<ref name=fract>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=764753&sec=england&cc=5901 Fabregas out for six weeks with leg fracture], ESPNsoccernet, 1 April 2010, accessed 2 April 2010.</ref> Arsenal, who were four points behind league leaders Manchester United, were deprived of their captain for the remaining six league games of the season;<ref name=fract/> they were subsequently eliminated by Barcelona in the Champions League, and fell out of the league title race. Fàbregas was later named to the [[PFA Team of the Year#Premier League 3|PFA Team of the Year]].<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=777236&sec=england&cc=5901 Rooney scoops PFA Player of the Year Award], ESPNsoccernet, 25 April 2010, accessed 26 April 2010.</ref>

[[File:Busquets, Fàbregas & Van Persie.jpg|thumb|upright|Fàbregas tries to subdue an argument between [[Sergio Busquets]] and [[Robin van Persie]].]]
Before the start of the [[2010–11 in English football|2010–11 season]], there was once again intense media speculation about the Spaniard's future, and in June 2010, a €35&nbsp;million bid from Barcelona was rejected.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/8717785.stm Arsenal reject Barcelona's bid for Cesc Fabregas], BBC Sport, 2 June 2010, accessed 15 June 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1282129/Barcelona-switch-tactics-Cesc-Fabregas-bid-Arsenal-negotiating-table.html Barcelona switch tactics over Cesc Fabregas in bid to get Arsenal to the negotiating table], ''The Daily Mail'', 28 May 2010, accessed 22 June 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada09-10/06/04/n100604111383.html Laporta: Lines of communication open over Cesc], fcbarcelona.cat, 4 June 2010, accessed 27 June 2010.</ref> The 2010–11 season turned out to be an extremely competitive one in the Premier League; even though Arsenal had lost five games before mid-season, they were jostling for pole position with Manchester United and Manchester City.<ref>Roger, Martins, [http://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/news?slug=ro-eplmidtermgrades122910 "EPL midseason surprises and disappointments"], Yahoo! Sports, 29 December 2010, accessed 20 January 2011.</ref> Going into late February, Arsenal were still in contention for the quadruple, but within a span of two weeks they lost in the [[2011 Football League Cup Final|League Cup final]], were eliminated by Barcelona in the Round of 16 of the [[UEFA Champions League 2010–11|Champions League]], and defeated in the FA Cup quarter-final.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/893940/arsene-wenger-not-questioning-arsenal-players'-steel?cc=4716 Wenger not questioning steel], ESPNsoccernet, 14 March 2011, accessed 15 March 2011.</ref> Although Fàbregas did not play in the League Cup Final, it was his misplaced backheel pass during the second leg of the Champions League game against Barcelona that allowed them to level the aggregate score. Arsenal remained in contention for the league title until a series of draws in the final third of the season caused them to fall too far behind league leaders Manchester United; they ended the season fourth. The [[2011–12 in English football|following season]] was once again marked by uncertainty. Barcelona made several bids for Fàbregas, while Nasri, Arsenal's star performer the previous campaign, was courted by Manchester City.

=== Barcelona ===

==== 2011–12 season ====

[[File:Cesc Fàbregas - Presentation.jpg|thumb|Fàbregas during his presentation to Barcelona]]
On 15 August 2011, Barcelona signed Fàbregas for an initial fee of €29&nbsp;million with a further €5&nbsp;million in variables, plus Fàbregas would pay Arsenal €1&nbsp;million a year from his wage for five years.<!-- NOTE: do not change this sourced amount. Failure to respect sourced material will result in a vandalism block. Be aware. --><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/season/2011-2012/bartomeu-thanks-cesc-for-his-efforts-to-come-to-barca|title=Bartomeu thanks Cesc for his efforts to come to Barça |date=15 August 2011|accessdate=7 August 2012|publisher=FC Barcelona}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/943939|title=Fabregas arrives for medical|date=15 August 2011|accessdate=13 June 2014|publisher=ESPN SOCCERNET}}</ref> ending one of the most protracted transfer sagas in recent times. Statistics show that in the five years prior to Fàbregas's departure from Arsenal, Fàbregas created 466 goal-scoring chances, made 86 assists and scored 48 goals, all three statistics topping those of new teammates [[Xavi|Xavi Hernández]] and [[Andrés Iniesta]] despite both having made more appearances in the same period.<ref>[http://football-talk.co.uk/31566/official-fabregas-is-better-than-xavi-iniesta.stm "OFFICIAL: Fabregas Is Better Than Xavi & Iniesta"], Football-Talk, 20 July 2011, accessed 26 July 2012.</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14482418.stm "Cesc Fabregas completes move from Arsenal to Barcelona"], BBC Sport, 15 August 2011, accessed 15 August 2011.</ref>

Fàbregas joined a team that had won three [[List of Spanish football champions|La Liga titles]] in a row and two Champions League titles in three years, and one that featured the likes of [[Lionel Messi]], Xavi Hernández, Andrés Iniesta and [[David Villa]]. He made his debut in the second leg of the [[Supercopa de España]], coming on as a substitute against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]. Barcelona won the tie 3–2 and 5–4 on aggregate.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/330063 Messi wins Super Cup], ESPNsoccernet, 17 August 2011, accessed 17 August 2011.</ref> He scored his first goal in a 2–0 win against [[FCPorto|Porto]] as Barcelona won the [[2011 UEFA Super Cup]],<ref>Ashby, Kevin, [http://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/season=2011/matches/round=2000258/match=2006776/postmatch/report/index.html "Barcelona breeze to fourth UEFA Super Cup"], UEFA, 26 August 2011, accessed 27 August 2011.</ref> and his first league goal on his league debut against [[Villarreal CF]]. He went on to score three more league goals in the month of September, including a late equaliser in the 2–2 away draw to [[Valencia CF]].<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/sep/22/valencia-barcelona-la-liga Late goal from Cesc Fábregas earns Barcelona a draw with Valencia], The Guardian, 22 September 2011, accessed 1 January 2013.</ref>

Fàbregas then spent the majority of October sidelined with a hamstring injury picked up on international duty. He made his return, and scored, in a 4–0 away victory to [[FC Viktoria Plzeň]] in the [[2011–12 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]. He then made his league return in the 2–2 draw away to [[Athletic Bilbao]], scoring a goal in the same match. Fàbregas then went on to score a brace in a 5–0 home victory against [[Levante UD]] before netting in a 3–1 away victory against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]. Fàbregas later scored against [[Santos FC]] to help Barcelona to a 4–0 victory in the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup]] final.

Fàbregas got another brace in a 4–0 victory against [[CA Osasuna]] in the [[2011–12 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]]. He also scored in the semi-final of the competition against Valencia to help Barcelona to the final with a 3–1 win on aggregate. He kept a regular run in the Barcelona side for the rest of the season, including appearances in both semi-final legs of the 3–2 aggregate defeat to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the Champions League, and a substitute appearance in the 3–0 victory against Athletic Bilbao in the [[2012 Copa del Rey Final|Copa del Rey final]].

Fàbregas ended his first season at Barcelona by winning the [[2011–12 Copa del Rey]], [[2011 Supercopa de España]], [[2011 UEFA Super Cup]] and the [[2011 FIFA Club World Cup]], notching 15 goals and 20 assists in 48 appearances and four best midfielder awards.

==== 2012–13 season ====

Fàbregas ended his long goal drought for his club when he scored his first league goals of the season with a brace against [[Sevilla FC]] in a 3–2 away victory. He then scored three goals in October, coming in the league, [[2012–13 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and the [[2012–13 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]]. He scored again on 25 November in a 4–0 win away to [[Levante UD]]. On 13 January 2013, Fàbregas scored in a 3–1 win away to [[Málaga CF]]. Fàbregas scored his first [[hat-trick]] of his career against [[RCD Mallorca]] in a 5–0 victory on 6 April 2013. He ended his second season at Barcelona by winning the first [[2012–13 La Liga|league title]] of his career, with a record 100 points. Barcelona were eliminated, however, in the semi-finals of both the Copa del Rey, to rivals Real Madrid, and the Champions League, to winners [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]. Fàbregas ended the season with 14 goals and 12 assists in 48 appearances in all competitions.

==== 2013–14 season ====

Barcelona began the season by winning the [[2013 Supercopa de España|Supercopa de España]]. In the opening game of the [[2013–14 La Liga|league season]] on 18 August, Fàbregas provided five assists in a 7–0 win over [[Levante UD|Levante]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Barcelona 7-0 Levante: Stunning debut win for Tata Martino|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/barcelona-vs-levante/1517627/report|accessdate=12 June 2014|work=Goal.com|date=18 August 2014}}</ref> He scored 8 goals in 36 league matches, including braces in away wins over [[Granada CF|Granada]] on 10 November and [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] on 22 December, the latter including a penalty kick. He also scored the only goal of the game on 1 October as Barcelona won away at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in the Group Stage of the Champions League, heading in [[Alexis Sánchez]]'s cross in the 73rd minute.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bogunya|first1=Roger|title=Barça show they learnt last year's lesson|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/match-archive/2013-2014/champions-league/round-2-h/celtic_fc-barcelona/info|accessdate=12 June 2014|publisher=[[FC Barcelona]]}}</ref>

=== Chelsea ===
[[File:Chelsea 2 QPR 1 (15662596926).jpg|thumb|200px|Fàbregas in action against [[Karl Henry]] of [[Queens Park Rangers]] in November 2014]]
On 12 June 2014, English [[Premier League]] team [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] signed Fàbregas on a five-year contract for a fee in the region of €33&nbsp;million. Following his transfer he took the number 4 shirt, previously worn by [[David Luiz]].<ref name=chelsea>{{cite news|title=Cesc Fabregas: Chelsea sign ex-Arsenal midfielder from Barcelona|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27819204|accessdate=12 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news-article/article/3900839/title/fabregas-signs-for-chelsea|title=FABREGAS SIGNS FOR CHELSEA|date=12 June 2014|accessdate=13 June 2014|publisher=Chelsea FC}}</ref> Fàbregas spoke of his transfer, saying, "I asked Barcelona to find a way for me to leave the club, The president tried to stop the sale, but I already had my mind made up." He went on to say, "If I didn't think that I'd be happy at Chelsea, I would've never made this decision. Above all, I want to be happy both professionally and personally."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11668/9351623/transfer-news-cesc-fabregas-insists-he-told-barcelona-he-wanted-to-leave|title=Cesc Fabregas insists he told Barcelona he wanted to leave|date=17 June 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014|publisher=Chelsea FC}}</ref>

==== 2014–15 season ====

Fàbregas made his competitive debut for Chelsea on 18 August as the team began their league season away to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]; he played the full 90 minutes of a 3–1 victory, providing two assists.<ref>{{cite news|title=Burnley 1-3 Chelsea|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28735901|accessdate=18 August 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=18 August 2014}}</ref> He was a nominee for the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] in August 2014, with the accolade going instead to another new Chelsea signing, [[Diego Costa]].<ref name=august>{{cite news|title=Diego Costa accepts August accolade|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2014/09/diego-costa-accepts-august-accolade.html?WT.mc_id=social_20140912_31482496|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=[[Chelsea F.C.]]|date=12 September 2014}}</ref> On 13 September 2014, after providing two assists in Chelsea's 4–2 victory over [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], Fàbregas became the first player ever in Premier League history to record at least one assist in six successive games; four under Chelsea and two under Arsenal during the [[2010–11 Arsenal F.C. season|2010&ndash;11 season]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Crooks|first1=Garth|title=Garth Crooks's team of the week|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29200736|accessdate=17 September 2014|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 September 2014}}</ref> Four days later he scored his first goal for the club, opening a 1–1 draw at home against [[Schalke 04]] in Chelsea's first match of the [[2014–15 UEFA Champions League group stage|Champions League group stage]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea 1-1 Schalke|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29225452|accessdate=17 September 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=17 September 2014}}</ref>

His first league goal for Chelsea gave them a 2&ndash;1 win at [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 18 October, capping off a 19-pass move.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fifield|first1=Dominic|title=Chelsea stay top after Cesc Fàbregas nets winner at Crystal Palace|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/oct/18/crystal-palace-chelsea-premier-league-match-report|accessdate=18 October 2014|work=The Guardian|date=18 October 2014}}</ref> Fàbregas also completed 123 passes, the most by any player on either side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29580146 |title=Cesc Fabregas scored his first league goal for Chelsea as the Premier League leaders survived a late Crystal Palace fightback to maintain a five-point advantage over Manchester City. |work=BBC Sport |date=18 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014 }}</ref> On 10 December, with Chelsea already through to the knockout stage as group winners, Fàbregas scored an eighth-minute penalty to open a 3&ndash;1 Champions League victory over [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Adam|title=Chelsea 3-1 Sporting|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29363859|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=10 December 2014}}</ref> Twelve days later he scored a second league goal, set up by [[Eden Hazard]] and concluding a 2&ndash;0 win away to Stoke.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Strickland|first1=Jamie|title=Stoke 0-2 Chelsea|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30474063|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=22 December 2014}}</ref>

Fàbregas was fitted with a protective mask after breaking his nose in a collision with [[Charlie Adam]] during the reverse fixture on 4 April.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas to wear face mask after breaking nose - report|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chelsea/story/2388491/chelsea-midfielder-cesc-fabregas-to-wear-face-mask-after-breaking-nose-report|accessdate=16 April 2015|publisher=ESPN|date=9 April 2015}}</ref> Eight days later, he scored the only goal of the game in the 88th minute in a victory over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Loftus Road]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=Glenn|title=QPR vs Chelsea match report: Man in the mask Cesc Fabregas secures vital win in Premier League title race|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/qpr-vs-chelsea-match-report-man-in-the-mask-cesc-fabregas-secures-vital-win-in-premier-league-title-race-10171035.html|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=The Independent|date=12 April 2015}}</ref> On 3 May, the day before his 28th birthday, he won his first Premier League title at the ninth attempt, following a 1–0 home win over Crystal Palace.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morlidge|first1=Matt|title=Chelsea midfielder Cesc Fabregas enjoys 28th birthday with family one day after securing Premier League title|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3067471/Chelsea-midfielder-Cesc-Fabregas-enjoys-28th-birthday-family-one-day-securing-Premier-League-title.html|accessdate=4 May 2015|work=Daily Mail|date=4 May 2015}}</ref> During the penultimate game of the season away at [[The Hawthorns]] against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], Fàbregas  was shown the red card and booed off by fans for deliberately kicking the ball at [[Chris Brunt]]'s head while players were speaking to referee [[Mike Jones (referee)|Mike Jones]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/cesc-fabregas-sent-kicking-ball-5720196|title=Cesc Fabregas sent off for kicking the ball into West Brom player's HEAD after melee|author=James Whaling|date=18 May 2015|work=Daily Mirror|accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref> On appeal, the suspension for this red card was cut from three matches to one.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cesc Fabregas: Chelsea player's ban cut from three games to one|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32819923|accessdate=21 May 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=20 May 2015}}</ref>

==== 2015–16 season ====

Fàbregas scored his first goal of the season as [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] defeat [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]] 4–0.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34203636 |first=Andy |last=Cryer |title=Chelsea 4–0 Maccabi Tel Aviv|website=BBC Sport |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>

== International career ==

=== Youth team ===

Although he features regularly for the [[Spain national football team]], Fàbregas' international career began at youth level. At the [[2003 FIFA U-17 World Championship]] held in Finland, he finished as top scorer of the tournament despite playing in midfield, and was voted Player of the Tournament.<ref name=uefap/> Spain finished runners-up in the tournament to Brazil.<ref>[http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=102/edition=6946/news/newsid=88795.html Brazil roar past brave Spain, Argentina take third], FIFA, 30 August 2003, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> Fàbregas was next involved in the [[UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship|2004 UEFA U-17 European Championship]], where Spain also finished runners-up.<ref name=uefa17>Haslam, Andrew, [http://www.uefa.com/competitions/under17/news/kind=2/newsid=522833.html "2004: Cesc Fabregas"], UEFA, accessed 9 July 2008. {{Wayback|df=yes|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/under17/news/kind=2/newsid=522833.html|date =20080526211523|bot=DASHBot}}</ref> He was named the Golden Player of the tournament by FIFA.<ref name=uefa17/>

=== Senior team ===

After emerging as one of Arsenal's key players in only his second season at the club, it did not take long for Fàbregas to be called up to the senior squad. Noting his impressive performances in Arsenal's 2006 Champions League campaign, Spain coach [[Luis Aragonés]] named the teenager in the team for a [[friendly match|friendly]] against [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]].<ref name=Spain>Harris, Chris, [http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/fabregas-why-i-feel-part-of-the-spain-family- "Fabregas – Why I feel part of the Spain 'family'"], Arsenal F.C., 28 March 2007, accessed 24 May 2007.</ref> In that game, Fàbregas became the youngest player [[cap (sport)|capped]] for Spain in 70 years, beating [[Sergio Ramos]]' record.<ref name=espn/> He received favourable reviews for his début, and was involved in the build-up to Spain's first goal in the 3–2 victory over the Ivorians.<ref name=espn/><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/4765086.stm Ivory Coast suffer defeat], BBC Sport, 2 March 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref>

==== 2006 World Cup ====

On 15 May 2006, Fàbregas was selected for the Spanish [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] squad. During the tournament, he came on as a second-half substitute in Spain's first two group matches, contributing an assist to striker [[Fernando Torres]] in their 3–1 victory against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853264.stm Spain 3–1 Tunisia], BBC Sport, 19 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> He then started alongside Spain's reserve players (including then-Arsenal teammate [[José Antonio Reyes]]) in Spain's third group match against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853438.stm Saudi Arabia 0–1 Spain], BBC Sport, 23 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> He earned a starting role in Spain's first knockout-stage match against [[France national football team|France]], in place of [[Marcos Senna]], but Spain lost 3–1.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991524.stm Spain 1–3 France], BBC Sport, 27 June 2006, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref> Fàbregas also became the youngest player in Spanish football history to participate in a [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] when he came on as a substitute for [[Luis Javier García Sanz|Luis García]] after 77 minutes in the 4–0 victory against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] on 13 June 2006; he was then 19 years and 41 days old.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852902.stm Spain 4–0 Ukraine], BBC Sport, 14 June 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He was later nominated for the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Best Young Player Award|Gillette Young Player]] of the World Cup, but [[Germany national football team|Germany]]'s [[Lukas Podolski]] won the award.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/sports/worldcup2006/storyview.html?/story/worldcup2006/national/2006/07/07/fifa-youngplayer-podolski.html Germany's Podolski named top young player], CBC.ca, 7 July 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref>

==== UEFA Euro 2008 ====

[[File:Spain Euro 08 celebration 2.jpg|thumb|Fàbregas celebrating Spain's Euro 2008 championship]]
In [[UEFA Euro 2008]], Fàbregas was handed the [[squad number]] 10, rather than 18 which he had previously held.<ref>Veysey, Wayne, [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2008/05/28/sfnars228.xml "Cesc Fabregas ready to talk tough with Arsenal"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 28 May 2008, accessed 10 June 2008.</ref> Despite featuring mostly as a substitute, the midfielder made a considerable impact in Spain's campaign. He scored his first international goal in that competition in Spain's 4–1 win over [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and also had an assist in that game.<ref name=cescteam>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/cesc-in-euro-2008-team-of-the-tournament Cesc in Euro 2008 Team of the Tournament], Arsenal F.C., accessed 6 August 2008.</ref> Spain won all three of their group games and met [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the quarter-finals. In that match, Fàbregas scored the winning penalty in the [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] after the teams remained deadlocked 0–0 after extra time.<ref>[http://soccernet-akamai.espn.go.com/report?id=232283&cc=4716 Spain beat Italy in penalty shootout], ESPNsoccernet, 22 June 2008, accessed 23 June 2008.</ref> In the semi-finals, Spain defeated Russia 3–0 with Fàbregas providing two assists.<ref name=cescteam/> The midfielder made the starting eleven in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|Final]] against Germany where Spain prevailed 1–0; this was Spain's first major title since 1964.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232286&cc=4716 Germany 0–1 Spain: Torres ends Spain's pain], ESPNsoccernet, 30 June 2008, accessed 30 June 2008.</ref> For his efforts, Fàbregas was named in the Team of the Tournament, a 23-man squad selected by the UEFA Technical Team.<ref name=cescteam/>

==== 2009 Confederations Cup ====

After missing out for several months due to his injury, Fàbregas regained his place as a regular in [[Vicente del Bosque]]'s squad. In June, he was named in the team for the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]]. He scored his second international goal in a 5–0 win against [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] in the competition's group stage.<ref>[http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round=250116/match=66203/summary.html Torres stars in Spanish stroll], FIFA, accessed 15 June 2009.</ref> In the semi-finals against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] (which Fàbregas started), Spain suffered a shock 2–0 loss, and its 15-game winning streak came to an end.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=270153&cc=4716 Altidore's goal leads U.S. to stunning upset], ESPNsoccernet, 24 June 2009, accessed 26 June 2009.</ref>

==== 2010 World Cup ====

[[File:Cesc Fàbregas and Giorgio Chiellini Euro 2012 final.jpg|thumb|Fàbregas during the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final]]]]
Fàbregas was selected as a part of del Bosque's 23-man squad for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8695232.stm Spain omit Marcos Senna from 2010 World Cup squad], BBC Sport, 20 May 2010, accessed 22 May 2010.</ref> With del Bosque preferring a starting midfield of [[Sergio Busquets]], [[Xabi Alonso]], [[Xavi]] and [[Andrés Iniesta]], Fàbregas did not start in any of Spain's games in the competition. He featured as a substitute in four of their seven matches, in which Spain lost their opening game before winning the next six en route to [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]]. In the Final itself, Fàbregas set up the extra-time winner for Iniesta to win Spain the World Cup for the first time in their history.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=264123&cc=4716&league=FIFA.WORLD&ver=global Iniesta sinks Dutch with late strike], ESPNsoccernet, 11 July 2010, accessed 13 July 2010.</ref>

==== UEFA Euro 2012 ====

Fàbregas was selected as a part of del Bosque's 23-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2012]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18227019
| title=Spain name Fernando Torres in 23-man squad|date=27 May 2012|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 June 2012 }}</ref>
Fàbregas started in the front three of a 4–3–3 formation against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in Spain's opening [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group C|Group C]] match. In the 64th minute he scored the equaliser after Italy had taken the lead in the 61st minute; the game finished in a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18180099|title=Spain 1–1 Italy |date=10 June 2012|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 June 2012 }}</ref> He then scored his second goal of the tournament in the group stage match against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]]. When Spain faced [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in the semi-finals and the game remained scoreless at the end of extra time, Fàbregas scored the winning penalty of the shootout as Spain prevailed 4–2. In the final against Italy, Fàbregas started and provided the assist to [[David Silva]] for the game's opening goal, en route to a 4–0 Spain victory.

==== 2013 Confederations Cup ====

Fàbregas was named in the provisional squad in the lead up to the [[2013 Confederations Cup]] by del Bosque.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/confed-cup-spain-name-provisional-squad-for-nigeria-others|title=Confed Cup:Spain name provisional squad for Nigeria, others|date=27 May 2013|work=futaa.com|accessdate=16 July 2013 }}</ref> He made two starts in the competition and one substitute appearance, all during the group stage of the competition, and assisting a goal in Spain's opening group match against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], which Spain won 2-1.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 FIFA Confederations Cup - Group B - Spain vs. Uruguay: 2-1|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/97895/spain-vs-uruguay/report?|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref> Spain won all their group matches, only conceding a goal and scoring 15. Spain advanced to the final of the competition for the first time, after a lengthy and difficult semi-final clash in a re-match against their opponents of the [[Euro 2012 final|European Championship Final]] of the previous year, [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. The match ended 0–0 after extra time and Spain won 7–6 in the resulting penalty shoot-out, but were eventually defeated 3–0 in the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|final]] by hosts and defending champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].

==== 2014 World Cup ====

Fàbregas was named in Spain's 30-man provisional squad for the World Cup,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27394287|title=World Cup 2014: Diego Costa and Fernando Torres in Spain squad|work=BBC Sport|date=13 May 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> and was also included in the final list for the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27647635|title=World Cup 2014: Spain drop Alvaro Negredo and Jesus Navas|work=BBC Sport|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> He made his debut in the tournament in the opening 1–5 defeat to the Netherlands, replacing [[David Silva]] for the last 12 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285043|title=Spain 1–5 Netherlands|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 June 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> With Spain already eliminated, he played 22 minutes of 3–0 win against [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] in the last group game, this time in place of [[Santi Cazorla]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285263|title=Australia 0–3 Spain|publisher=BBC Sport|last1=Chowdhury|first1=Saj|date=23 June 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref>

====UEFA Euro 2016====
On 31 March 2015, Fàbregas [[Captain (association football)|captained]] Spain for the first time, in their 0–2 friendly defeat to the Netherlands at the [[Amsterdam Arena]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Internationals: Belgium hold on, Fabregas captains Spain|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2015/03/internationals--belgium-hold-on--fabregas-captains-spain.html|accessdate=12 June 2015|publisher=Chelsea F.C.|date=31 March 2015}}</ref> He earned his [[FIFA Century Club|100th cap]] on 12 October 2015, becoming the tenth Spaniard to do so, in a [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] match against {{nft|Ukraine}} with Spain already qualified.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Myson|first1=Chris|title=Fabregas makes 100th Spain appearance|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/88/spain/2015/10/12/16259312/fabregas-makes-100th-spain-appearance|accessdate=13 October 2015|publisher=Goal.com|date=12 October 2015}}</ref> In his milestone match at the [[Olympic Stadium (Kiev)|Olympic Stadium]] in [[Kiev]], he won a first-half penalty when fouled by [[Oleksandr Kucher]], but his spot kick was saved by [[Andriy Pyatov]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ukraine 0-1 Spain: Fabregas misses penalty on 100th appearance|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/ukraine-vs-spain/1653387/report|accessdate=13 October 2015|publisher=Goal.com|date=12 October 2015}}</ref>

== Style of play ==

=== Arsenal and Chelsea ===

[[File:Cesc Fabregas v LCFC 2014 02.jpg|thumb|260px|upright|Fàbregas playing for Chelsea in 2014]]
Originally brought to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] as a youth to slowly develop via the League Cup, Fàbregas was unexpectedly deployed as Arsenal's starting [[Centre midfield|central midfielder]] following injuries to fellow midfielders [[Patrick Vieira]], [[Gilberto Silva]] and [[Eduardo César Gaspar|Edu]] during the 2004–05 season. While [[defensive midfielder]] Vieira served as his role model and mentor,<ref>Townsend, Nick, [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20051002/ai_n15644739 "Spanish marvel blossoms"], ''The Independent'', 2 October 2005, accessed 17 September 2007. {{Wayback|df=yes|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20051002/ai_n15644739|date =20080314115614|bot=DASHBot}}</ref> he styled his game after his childhood hero and compatriot [[Josep Guardiola]]; whose shirt number 4 he would inherit in his subsequent move to Barcelona in 2011.<ref name=times/> Because he was of a different mould from his Arsenal predecessors who played in the same position,<ref name=times/><ref name=hubb/> this led to criticisms of his lightweight frame and less aggressive style of play, due to his development in the [[La Masia|Barcelona Youth Academy]],<ref name=hubb/><ref name=harr/> with former teammate [[Ashley Cole]] criticising the Spaniard as "an unproven featherweight" in his autobiography.<ref>Macintosh, Iain, "Completely Fab", ''The New Paper'', 29 September 2007.</ref>

However, it did not take long for Fàbregas to become one of the most coveted and celebrated young talents in the game with his success at Arsenal. Functioning mostly as a [[playmaker]] and renowned for his passing range, he was described as the general of Arsenal's first team, bringing vision, creativity, and an innate understanding of timing and space to Arsenal's intricate passing game, displaying maturity that belied his age.<ref name=espn/><ref name=ars/><ref name=uefap/><ref name=fa/><ref name=pots/><ref name=chall/><ref name=skates>Smith, Alan, [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2007/01/20/sfnsmi20.xml "Fabregas puts his skates on in chase for perfection"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 20 January 2007, accessed 23 May 2007.</ref><ref>McIlvanney, Hugh, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2094-2104071,00.html "Fàbregas a leader in waiting"], ''The Times'', 26 March 2006, accessed 22 May 2007.</ref> He was the main creative force when he was at Arsenal, as exemplified by his 16 assists in all competitions in the 2006–07 season.<ref name=stats/> Between 2006–07 and 2010–11, Fàbregas created the most chances in the top-division leagues of England, Spain, Italy, Germany and France.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14491850.stm The magic of Cesc Fabregas], BBC Sport, 11 August 2011, accessed 15 August 2011.</ref>

At Arsenal, Fàbregas also often assumed responsibility for [[Set piece (football)|set pieces]], taking [[corner kick|corners]], [[Direct free kick|free kicks]] and [[Penalty kick|penalties]]. By his own admission, scoring was a weaker part of his game in his first few seasons at Arsenal; wasteful finishing also being symptomatic of the larger problem surrounding Arsenal in the 2005–06 and 2006–07 seasons.<ref name=skates/> This changed initially in the 2007–08 season when he scored 11 goals in his first 16 games, and Arsenal manager Wenger claimed that the Spaniard's previous inability to score was down to a mental state, and even compared the Spaniard to [[Michel Platini]], a French midfielder renowned for scoring.<ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/wenger-fabregas-has-the-vision-of-platini Wenger: Fabregas has the vision of Platini], Arsenal F.C., 19 September 2007, accessed 4 January 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/wenger-this-team-is-blossoming-and-growing- Wenger: 'This team is blossoming and growing'], Arsenal F.C., 15 September 2007, accessed 17 September 2007.</ref> There were also concerns raised over the large number of games Fàbregas was playing for club and country at such a young age,<ref name=Spain/><ref>van Wijk, Jim, [http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/premiership/article2401632.ece "Fabregas in need of rest after season of hard work"], ''The Independent'', 29 March 2007, accessed 24 May 2007.</ref> but while he initially avoided long spells on the sidelines, he played significantly fewer games due to injury in his last three seasons with Arsenal.

At Chelsea, Fàbregas played a similar [[Playmaker|playmaking]] role in midfield, using his technique, ball control, vision, and passing ability to dictate the tempo of his team's play, while he was supported by defensive midfielders, in order to give him more space and time on the ball.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cesc Fabregas happy pulling the strings from Chelsea's midfield|url=http://www.espnfc.com/chelsea/story/2200896/chelseas-cesc-fabregas-believes-his-good-form-in-the-premier-league-is-due-to-his-deployment-his-favoured-central-midfield-role|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> In this deeper creative role,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cesc Fabregas Says He is Thriving in Deeper Chelsea Role|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/cesc-fabregas-says-he-thriving-deeper-chelsea-role-1470915|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> he excelled in Chelsea's new style of play under Mourinho,<ref>{{cite web|title=Cesc Fabregas believes Chelsea success down to Jose Mourinho playing him in the right position|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/cesc-fabregas-believes-chelsea-success-4816953|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> where he proved to be an effective [[Assist (football)|assist]]-provider.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cesc Fàbregas|url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/38886/cesc-fabregas|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas: My favourite assists|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/players/cesc-fabregas/11370990/Chelseas-Cesc-Fabregas-My-favourite-assists.html|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea midfielder Cesc Fabregas: I am playing the best football of my life|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/11256429/Chelsea-midfielder-Cesc-Fabregas-I-am-playing-the-best-football-of-my-life.html|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chelsea's Cesc Fabregas: Thierry Henry assist record 'not an obsession'|url=http://www.espnfc.com/barclays-premier-league/story/2267016/chelseas-cesc-fabregas-thierry-henry-assist-record-for-arsenal-not-an-obsession|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>

=== Barcelona and Spain ===

At Barcelona, Fàbregas continued to play a prominent [[midfield]] and [[Playmaker|playmaking]] role, although he was moved into a more offensive position than that which he had occupied at Arsenal. His new role with Barcelona was comparable to that which he had played with the [[Spanish national football team|Spanish national team]]. He effortlessly fit into [[Pep Guardiola]]'s 4-3-3 formation, participating in the midfield's trademark [[Tiki-taka|"tiki-taka"]] patient, attacking, build-up style of play, also associated with the Spanish National Squad under Vincente Del Bosque and [[Luis Aragonés]]. Fàbregas was used in a variety of different roles under Guardiola, scoring several goals and providing many assists. Due to the presence of [[Xavi]], [[Sergio Busquets]] and [[Andrés Iniesta]] in the three man midfield, as well as the emerging [[Thiago Alcântara|Thiago]], however, Fàbregas was often employed out of position as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]], or even as a supporting [[Forward (association football)|forward]] under Guardiola. He regularly performed in the role that [[Lionel Messi]] had often occupied during the previous season, functioning as a [[False nine|false-9]] in a [[Formation (association  football)#4–6–0|4–6–0 formation]] (a role which he would also play for Spain at [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] under [[Vicente del Bosque]]),<ref>{{cite web|title=False nine Fabregas shows his importance, and more|url=http://chroniclesofalmunia.wordpress.com/2012/06/11/false-nine-fabregas-shows-his-importance-and-more/|accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> whilst Messi would play as a right winger or second forward.<ref>{{cite web|title=Guardiola's Barcelona-Reinventing Total Football|url=http://www.thefalse9.com/2012/04/guardiolas-barcelona-reinventing-total.html|accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref> Fàbregas was, however, still used in deeper roles on occasion, as an attacking, deep-lying or central playmaking midfielder, in particular under Guardiola's successors [[Tito Vilanova]] and [[Tata Martino]].

